  "prompt": "Where can I find a training data set (free or not) for patent/prior art search to train a deep learning engine to select relevant prior art/ patents?",
  "response": "When looking for datasets to train a deep learning model for patent and prior art searches, there are several resources you can explore, both free and paid:\n\n### Free Resources:\n\n1. **USPTO Public Pair**:\n   - The United States Patent and Trademark Office (USPTO) provides a wealth of data, including published patent applications and granted patents. You can access this data via the USPTO\u2019s Public PAIR (Patent Application Information Retrieval) system.\n\n2. **Google Patents**:\n   - Google Patents allows you to search through millions of patents and patent applications. You can extract data using their API or directly from the website.\n\n3. **European Patent Office (EPO) - Espacenet**:\n   - Espacenet offers access to information about inventions and technical developments from the 19th century to today. They also have bulk download options available for certain datasets.\n\n4. **PatentsView**:\n   - PatentsView provides a number of patent datasets that can be accessed via their API. They offer a variety of data points on patents and can be useful for training purposes.\n\n5. **Kaggle**:\n   - Kaggle hosts various datasets contributed by users, and you might find some related to patents or scientific papers. You can explore datasets from the Kaggle Datasets repository.\n\n6. **Semantic Scholar**:\n   - While not specifically for patents, Semantic Scholar provides a dataset of scientific papers, which might be useful in conjunction with patent data for prior art searches.\n\n7. **Open Patents**:\n   - This is an initiative that provides datasets related to patents that may be useful for research and model training.\n\n### Paid or Commercial Resources:\n\n1. **LexisNexis\u00ae PatentAdvisor\u00ae**:\n   - A subscription-based service that provides access to comprehensive patent information and analysis tools. It can be expensive but offers proprietary insights.\n\n2. **Questel - Orbit**:\n   - Offers advanced patent databases and tools specifically designed for IP professionals, available through a subscription.\n\n3. **Innography**:\n   - Also a paid service, it gives access to analysis tools and databases that can help in assessing patent landscapes and related prior art.\n\n4. **Clarivate - Derwent Innovation**:\n   - A powerful commercial tool for patent analytics and prior art searches, aimed at professionals in the field.\n\n### Other Considerations:\n\n- **Data Licensing**: Always check the licensing terms for any dataset you plan to use, especially if you intend to commercialize your model.\n  \n- **Data Quality**: Ensure that the quality and relevance of the datasets align with your training objectives. \n\n- **Synthetic Data**: If existing datasets don\u2019t meet your requirements, consider generating synthetic data, although this comes with its own set of challenges.\n\nFinally, consider joining relevant academic or professional forums where you might find more up-to-date recommendations on datasets tailored to your specific requirements in patent and prior art searches.",
